<methodology slug="best-practices-2026">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>software-developer</domain>
    <summary>2026-snapshot reference of current-stable practices across AI-assisted coding, TypeScript 5, React 19/Next.js 15, Python 3.12/3.13, and AI testing.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>best-practices</tag>
      <tag>typescript</tag>
      <tag>react</tag>
      <tag>python</tag>
      <tag>ai-coding</tag>
      <tag>testing</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Software Development Best Practices 2026</title>

    <summary>Stacks evolve faster than training data. Without an explicit current-state reference, agents default to training-era patterns: React 17 hooks, Optional[X] over X | None, outdated tsconfigs. This document provides a 2026-snapshot reference of current-stable practices across AI-assisted coding, TypeScript 5, React 19 / Next.js 15, Python 3.12/3.13, and AI-assisted testing. Use as a baseline for constitution extraction and code audits.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Stacks evolve faster than training data. Without an explicit current-state reference, agents default to training-era patterns: React 17 hooks, Optional[X] over X | None, outdated tsconfigs. This document provides a versioned baseline that can be diffed against a project's actual config and used to open upgrade tasks.</p>
      <p>This methodology is intended as a constitutional source: agents extract relevant clauses into .aidocs/constitution.md and make decisions from there, not from this file directly.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Bootstrapping a new TypeScript repo and pulling the strict tsconfig.json baseline.</item>
        <item>Designing a Next.js 15 App Router architecture: deciding Server vs Client boundaries.</item>
        <item>Modernizing a Python codebase to PEP 742 (TypeIs), PEP 705 (ReadOnly), asyncio.TaskGroup.</item>
        <item>Selecting AI coding tools (Claude Code, Cursor, Copilot) for a workflow segment.</item>
        <item>Selecting AI testing tools (Katalon, mabl, testRigor) and wiring them into CI.</item>
        <item>Auditing agent-generated code against "what current looks like."</item>
        <item>Writing or updating a project's .aidocs/constitution.md to encode 2026-current standards.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Legacy / LTS environments (Python 3.10, Node 18, React 17) — patterns here require newer runtimes.</item>
        <item>Embedded / WASM / extension contexts where RSC or pino are irrelevant.</item>
        <item>Static-site generators (Astro, Hugo, Gatsby) — the React 19 / Next.js 15 sections don't apply.</item>
        <item>Solo prototypes where strict tsconfig kills momentum; start strict on team projects.</item>
        <item>Greenfield tasks better served by a more specific sibling methodology.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <warning>
      <p>Time-bound by definition. "2026" snapshot ages fast — JIT/no-GIL Python, RSC, AI testing tools all evolve quarterly. Treat as last-known-good.</p>
      <p>Headline citations are blog-grade. Many sources are Medium/DEV posts, not vendor docs. Use them as starting pointers, not authority.</p>
      <p>Tool comparisons are marketing-shaped. Katalon/mabl/testRigor table omits cost, lock-in, and on-prem availability. Validate before adoption.</p>
      <p>AI risk numbers are unverified. "AI can increase defect rates 4x" is provocative but uncited; do not quote in critical decisions.</p>
      <p>Server Components: opinion as fact. "38% faster initial load" is a single benchmark; real apps see 0–60% depending on hydration profile.</p>
      <p>Python typing recommendations clash with library reality. from __future__ import annotations + Pydantic v1 / Django &lt; 5 still bites at runtime.</p>
      <p>JIT / no-GIL CPython are experimental as of 3.13; the content presents them as production-ready features. They are not.</p>
      <p>No coverage of tooling for AI safety (eval suites, red-teaming, CI checks for agent-generated code).</p>
      <p>No section on package management 2026 (uv, pnpm 9, bun, deno 2) — the team-level decisions that drive the rest of the stack.</p>
    </warning>

    <section name="ai-assisted-dev">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Match AI tool to task type: Copilot for daily inline completion, Cursor for exploratory multi-file edits, Claude Code for documentation / test suites / large refactors.</statement>
        <rationale>Each tool has a different context window, interaction model, and latency profile. Mixing them correctly multiplies productivity; using any single tool for all tasks degrades output quality.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Three-stage pipeline">
        <note>Claude Code for research/planning → Cursor for implementation flow → Copilot for inline completion.</note>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Structure every coding prompt with four parts: Context (stack, constraints), Task (specific action), Requirements (must-haves, edge cases), Output (expected format, file locations).</statement>
        <rationale>Unstructured prompts produce generic code that ignores project conventions. Four-part structure anchors the model to specifics.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never auto-accept AI-generated code for auth, data access, or business logic. Manual review is required for security-sensitive areas.</statement>
        <rationale>AI can increase defect rates significantly when used without review. Treat AI as assisted driving, not full self-driving.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Iterate: Draft → Review → Refine prompt → Regenerate → Final review. The first AI output is rarely production-ready.</statement>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Extract relevant clauses from this file into .aidocs/constitution.md for each project. Agents make runtime decisions from the constitution, not from this reference file.</statement>
        <rationale>This file is a 2026 snapshot and ages. The constitution is the versioned, project-specific contract that agents can cite in PRs without risking stale references.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Outdated React patterns inherited from training data.</description>
        <reason>Agents emit React.FC, useEffect for data fetching in App Router pages, or wrap server components with useState. Reject and re-prompt with the RSC boundary explicit.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Citing this file as authority.</description>
        <reason>Agents quote best-practices-2026/README.md in PRs as if it were a vendor doc. Force agents to cite the underlying source URL or, better, the project constitution clause.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Stale dep pins from training cut-off.</description>
        <reason>Agents pin next: "13.x" because that was current in training. Force ncu post-generation and reject training-anchored versions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="typescript-5">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Enable strict + noUncheckedIndexedAccess + exactOptionalPropertyTypes + verbatimModuleSyntax + moduleResolution bundler in every new TypeScript project.</statement>
        <rationale>These flags together catch the most common runtime errors at compile time. Piecemeal adoption creates inconsistent enforcement across the codebase.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/tsconfig-strict.json">2026-recommended strict tsconfig baseline</reference>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Adopt strict tsconfig in one PR. Flip all flags together; piecemeal adoption produces inconsistent enforcement.</statement>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use the satisfies operator over type assertion casts for config objects — it validates without widening.</statement>
        <rationale>satisfies catches mismatches at the definition site without losing precise inference, unlike explicit type annotations or as casts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="satisfies for config validation">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
const config = {
  port: 3000,
  host: 'localhost',
} satisfies ServerConfig;
// Type is inferred precisely, but validated against ServerConfig
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use const type parameters to preserve literal types in generic functions instead of widening to base types.</statement>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="const type parameters">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
function createConfig<const T extends readonly string[]>(items: T): T {
  return items;
}
const config = createConfig(['a', 'b', 'c']);
// Type: readonly ['a', 'b', 'c'] not string[]
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use unknown over any. Use type guards for runtime narrowing. Add explicit return types to all public functions.</statement>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using any to escape type pressure.</description>
        <reason>any disables all type checking for the value and any values derived from it. Every any is a deferred runtime error.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>any slips back in.</description>
        <reason>Default LLM output reaches for any under TypeScript pressure. Forbid via ESLint @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any and reject PRs that disable it inline without a reason.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Optional/Union regressions.</description>
        <reason>Agents alternate between int | None and Optional[int] within a file. Pick one (preferably the modern syntax) and lint.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="react19-nextjs15">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Default to Server Components. Add 'use client' only when the component needs interactivity (useState, useEffect, event handlers). Push interactivity to leaves.</statement>
        <rationale>Server Components send zero JavaScript to the client and can directly access databases and server-side resources. Overusing 'use client' inflates the bundle and negates RSC benefits.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Server Components can import Client Components. Client Components cannot import Server Components. Children of Client Components become Client Components.</statement>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding 'use client' to a layout component to "just make it work".</description>
        <reason>This flips the entire subtree client-side. The fix cascades bundle size into every page under that layout.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Validate all Server Action input with Zod before touching the database. Return { error } shapes for validation failures; never trust formData directly.</statement>
        <rationale>Server Actions run on the server but accept untrusted client data. Zod validation is the only reliable guard.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Server Action with Zod validation">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
'use server';
import { z } from 'zod';

const UserSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(2),
  email: z.string().email(),
});

export async function createUser(prevState: unknown, formData: FormData) {
  const result = UserSchema.safeParse({
    name: formData.get('name'),
    email: formData.get('email'),
  });
  if (!result.success) {
    return { error: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
  }
  await db.users.create(result.data);
  revalidatePath('/users');
  return { success: true };
}
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use route groups (marketing), parallel routes (@analytics), and intercepting routes ((.)photos) for layout composition without URL pollution.</statement>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Memoize data fetches shared between generateMetadata and the page component using React cache() to avoid double-fetching.</statement>
        <rationale>Both generateMetadata and the page component may call the same data-fetching function. Without cache(), the request fires twice per render.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Server Action without 'use server' directive.</description>
        <reason>Agents copy README snippets and skip the directive — function silently runs as a normal client function. Lint for the directive on every export named *Action or in actions.ts.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>use client cascading.</description>
        <reason>Adding 'use client' to a layout flips the entire subtree. Agents do this to "just make it work"; reviewer must catch.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>generateMetadata over-fetching.</description>
        <reason>Agents call getProduct(params.id) twice (once in metadata, once in page). Memoize via cache(...) or shared module-level promise.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>useFormState import path drift.</description>
        <reason>Renamed to useActionState in newer React; agents flip-flop. Pin React version + the matching API name in the constitution.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="python-3-13">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use X | None instead of Optional[X] in all new Python code. Use | union syntax instead of Union[X, Y].</statement>
        <rationale>PEP 604 (Python 3.10+) union syntax is shorter and consistent. Mixing old and new styles in one file creates noise and confuses readers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Protocol for structural typing instead of ABC when consumers define the interface, not the implementer.</statement>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Modern Python type hints">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from typing import Protocol, TypeIs, TypedDict, ReadOnly

# Modern union syntax
def process(value: int | str | None) -> str:
    return str(value) if value is not None else "None"

# ReadOnly fields in TypedDict (PEP 705)
class User(TypedDict):
    id: ReadOnly[int]
    name: str

# TypeIs for type narrowing (PEP 742)
def is_string_list(val: list[object]) -> TypeIs[list[str]]:
    return all(isinstance(x, str) for x in val)
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use asyncio.TaskGroup (Python 3.11+) for fan-out tasks instead of manual gather + error channels. Wrap with asyncio.timeout to prevent unbounded hangs.</statement>
        <rationale>TaskGroup automatically cancels siblings on first error and propagates exceptions cleanly. Unbounded fan-out without timeout will hang on slow downstream.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="asyncio.TaskGroup with timeout">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import asyncio

async def fetch_all():
    async with asyncio.timeout(10.0):
        async with asyncio.TaskGroup() as tg:
            users = tg.create_task(fetch_users())
            products = tg.create_task(fetch_products())
    return users.result(), products.result()
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap async fan-out with asyncio.Semaphore sized to downstream capacity (DB pool, API rate limit), not to CPU count.</statement>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="false">
        <statement>Do not use -X nogil or -X jit in production. Free-threaded CPython and JIT are experimental as of Python 3.13.</statement>
        <rationale>These features are not stable for production workloads. The no-GIL mode changes memory model assumptions that many C extensions rely on.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>No-GIL / JIT presented as stable.</description>
        <reason>Agents read the README and recommend python -X nogil for production. It is experimental in 3.13. Block this in the constitution.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>TaskGroup without timeouts.</description>
        <reason>Agents create unbounded TaskGroups; in production they hang on a slow downstream. Mandate async with asyncio.timeout(...) around groups.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-testing">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Evaluate AI testing tools across at least three dimensions before adoption: on-prem availability, pricing model, and lock-in risk. Do not select by recency bias.</statement>
        <rationale>The tool comparison tables in training data are marketing-shaped. Katalon/mabl/testRigor table omits cost, lock-in, and on-prem availability.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <note>AI Testing Tool Options:
        - Katalon — full QA platform, natural language to tests
        - mabl — AI-driven test creation, agile/DevOps oriented
        - testRigor — plain English tests for non-technical users
        - Virtuoso QA — self-healing tests for UI automation
        - LambdaTest KaneAI — LLM-powered cross-browser testing
      </note>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat AI-generated tests as a first draft. Human review and refinement is mandatory before merging. Never auto-merge AI-generated test files.</statement>
        <rationale>AI test tools generate flaky XPath-anchored tests, duplicate coverage, and cover trivial paths while missing critical ones. The human review step catches all three.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use role-based locators (ARIA roles, accessible names) in AI-generated UI tests. Reject XPath or CSS selector anchored tests as the primary locator strategy.</statement>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Accepting AI-generated test baselines in visual regression tools without human approval.</description>
        <reason>Agent accepting its own baselines defeats the purpose of visual regression testing. The first baseline must always be approved by a human.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>When using Claude Code to generate tests: specify the test framework, fixture strategy, AAA structure, and edge cases to cover explicitly in the prompt.</statement>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Claude Code test generation prompt">
        <note>Prompt: "Generate pytest tests for UserService. Cover: creation, validation, edge cases, error handling. Use baker fixtures, parametrize for value tables, AAA pattern. No mocks for in-app services."</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Snippet-level test generation.</description>
        <reason>AI test tools generate flaky XPath-anchored tests that break on first UI change. Always wrap with self-healing locators or migrate to role-based queries.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices-summary">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Project constitution > README. Always copy the relevant clauses into .aidocs/constitution.md with explicit overrides; never have agents read this file at runtime to make decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>The constitution is the versioned, project-specific contract that agents can cite in PRs without risking stale references.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pin language/runtime versions (engines.node, python_requires) to match the baseline. Drift is silent otherwise.</statement>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Log structured JSON, request_id everywhere. Both Node (pino) and Python (structlog) sections deserve uniform shape across services.</statement>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cite vendor docs over blog posts. When constitution clauses cite react.dev or python.org, agents have a stable source. Medium URLs rot.</statement>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run lychee on this README and the constitution monthly. Dead links signal stale guidance.</statement>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/tsconfig-strict.json" purpose="2026-recommended strict tsconfig baseline."/>
      <template path="templates/bp2026-drift.sh" purpose="Drift-detector: checks tsconfig, package.json, pyproject.toml against the 2026 baseline."/>
    </templates>

